default1.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClosing the social 
defaultclass achievement gap or ‘poverty gradient’ in education is a prominent policy reform issue in the UK, as it is in many other developed countries. And billions of pounds of public money has been, and is being, spent on generic or tailored intervention
defaults
default to 
defaultaddress it. However, these interventions are largely untested, or where they have been rigorously and independently evaluated they have been shown not to work or even to be harmful. 
default&#xa0;
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecent work has shown, for example, that almost all interventions to imp
defaultrove the attainment of disadvantaged pupils by altering attitudes, aspirations or behaviour have no evidence base or have been shown not to work (Gorard 2012). This is also so for attempts to improve post-compulsory participation, and applies to the attitu
defaultdes and behaviour of parents as well as young people and children. The same problem arises when assessing the evidence for interventions simply based on increasing or altering the timing and delivery mechanisms for education. Provision of summer schools, S
defaultaturday clubs, IT equipment and even teaching assistants in themselves make no difference (Gorard and See 2013). 
defaultAspiration without increased competence makes no difference whereas increased competence can lead to changes in aspiration, for example. In the
default same way, more school, faster delivery or smaller groups make no difference unless the activities undertaken are effective. But if the activities are effective then it is not clear that the others changes matter. A new example of this will be the first re
defaultport of a randomised controlled trial funded by the Educational Endowment Foundation (Gorard et al. 2013). Switch-on Reading was found to be a promisingly effective intervention for children moving to secondary school with low reading scores (around 3 mont
defaulths gain in reading age), capable of being conducted by teaching assistants. The intervention was most effective for the very lowest attainers, and those with special educational needs.
default&#xa0;
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the reasons why money is being directed towards unproven, ineff
defaultective or harmful interventions is that the quality of the 
defaultevidence available is generally so poor. And this is despite further billions of pounds of public money spent on generating such evidence. It is crucial that there is, in future, greater discrimina
defaulttion between attempts to provide good research evidence for wider use, and the rest. This is illustrated in the remainder of this submission by a summary of a new review of evidence 
defaultlinking interventions to improve parental engagement in their children’s e
defaultducation with improved attainment
default, conducted for the Nuffield Foundation
default (
defaultSee and 
defaultGorard 2013)
default. 
defaultThe review illustrates that there is not yet enough evidence that any intervention will work, and also that a far higher standard of basic evaluation is require
defaultd, and should be demanded by 
defaultall 
defaultfunders.
default The implications for policy-makers are in the final paragraphs 5.9 to 5.11. 
