default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have shown elsewhere, in a more widespread review, that there is plenty of reasonable descriptive evidence associating levels of parental involvement with levels of child attainment
default (Gorard
default et al. 2012)
default. The question this new review considered was whether the act of enhancing parental involvement through intervention leads to improved educational outcomes. This required a different kind of research design, of a substantial size, with a clear
default and fair counterfactual. We found no such study, and this has to be the headline finding for the review. Despite all of the practitioner, policy and state-funded investment in enhancing parental engagement in education across the world, we could not find 
defaultone high quality study that evaluated its impact. 
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis new review 
defaultincludes
default the highest quality evaluations 
defaultin terms of answering the key causal question about whether higher parental involvement creates higher attainment for their children
default. However
default, no 
defaultrelevant study was deemed to be high quality or e
defaultven anywhere near high quality. 
defaultEach study 
defaultlocated 
defaulthad 
defaultt
defaultwo
default or more
default serious flaw
defaults
