default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultMessages for funders
default&#xa0;
default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiven the absence of high quality evaluations encountered in this review, the first task of funders must be to remedy the situation. This can be done by calling for new primary research with specific characteristics, and ceasing to fund mere associational 
defaultor supposedly explanatory work in this area. The new research should be a fair test of whether the most promising approaches to enhancing parental involvement actually work in the sense of cost-effectively improving children’s subsequent attainment. The re
defaultsearch should involve several studies, both direct replications and of differing age groups, based in real-world settings. The design for each should be either a simple randomised comparison of a treatment and control group, or of an allocation using regre
defaultssion discontinuity. There should be around 1,000 pupils or more in each study, with very low attrition, perhaps through using a waiting-list design or other incentive to reduce post-allocation demoralisation, followed by an intention to treat analysis. 
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe procedures of the intervention and its evaluation should ideally be ‘blinded’ as far as possible, and 
defaultfor many steps this is simple (for example, by 
defaultconducting the pre-test for all cases before randomisation). The evaluation must be conducted by indivi
defaultduals with no concern for whether the intervention works or not, but concern only for finding out. The outcome measure used, such as a test of student learning, must be standardised, independent of the innovators of the intervention, and have real-world me
defaultaning (such as 
defaulta link to 
defaultKey Stage results). The intervention itself should be as simple as possible, not mixing parental involvement with any other elements of change or intervention (and applied only to the treatment group). After the intervention has be
defaulten completed for one large group but not the other, both groups should be assessed or measured for the single pre-specified outcome that the intervention was intended to improve. The result should be 
defaultbased on
default a simple comparison of the outcomes or gain sco
defaultres for each group.
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis advice is quite generic, and will apply to other topic areas as well, but it is necessary because of the very low level of quality found, even among the best evaluations. The level of work encountered is so far from that needed to
default answer relevant questions for public policy that even adopting these rather basic recommendations would lead to a considerable improvement. 
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMore generally, funders need to ensure that programmes and fields of research make suitable progress, or cease fu
defaultnding them. Research must work towards answers. This means that exploratory work is perfectly proper, but that when the results show promise the researchers must continue to developmental work, leading eventually to a fully-fledged trial. Good ideas must b
defaulte pursued to a gainful end in this way and poor ideas discarded. Currently too much work is mired in a repetitive phase of exploration without progress. This is an unethical use of t
defaultaxpayer and charitable funding.
default&#xa0;
defaultMessages for researchers
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo a large exte
defaultnt the implications for researchers follow those for funders. In this area, as in so many others, researchers must wake up to their ethical responsibilities to the public and to research funding bodies. They must see their work as part of an ongoing and la
defaultrger research cycle working towards an evaluation (of what works, a theory, or an artefact such as curriculum materials). They must ensure that promising work moves to a trial or other suitably rigorous evaluation phase, and that unpromising work ceases. I
defaultf they do not progress from exploration to development to trial then they must 
defaultreport
default that their early work is unpromising, so as to discourage wasteful investment of time and money by others. Finding out what does not work is therefore, almost, as valuabl
defaulte as finding what works.
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultResearchers must be independent of the interventions they are evaluating, and they must commission genuinely independent evaluations of any interventions they are developing.  They must care far more about getting the correct answ
defaulter to their research questions than about what that answer actually is. Almost as importantly, they must be more careful in describing and badging the kind of work they are currently conducting. They must eschew causal terms like ‘impact’ or ‘influence’ ex
defaultcept where their research designs permit or where the use is clearly speculative. 
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome of the generic problems with evaluation studies are quite alarming, and are nothing to do with those compromises sometimes necessary because of limited time, resources
default or data. Researchers are frequently quoting statistical significance and p-values with non-random samples not randomly allocated to groups, and this is as prevalent in supposedly peer-reviewed articles as in unpublished reports. And they are using the ‘si
defaultgnificance’ levels to try and decide whether an intervention has been effective or not. This is a widespread error, based on ignorance of sampling theory, 
defaultand it
default simply must cease. Researchers are also frequently presenting 
defaultsuch 
defaultanalyses based on individua
defaultl cases when they have allocated cases to treatment groups by classes, or even when there has been no allocation at all (such as when a matched comparator is created post hoc). A slightly less widespread but still important and dangerous 
defaultproblem
default is dredging for success. Many reports, even the better ones, are poorly written in the sense that they are vague or incomplete about basic facts such as numbers of cases, how they were selected and allocated and how much dropout or refusal there was. This
default may be carelessness. But some reports describe wider studies and several possible outcomes but only present the findings for outcomes that are deemed positive or desirable. This goes far beyond the possible file-drawer problem of unpublished negative find
defaultings. Authors themselves seem to want to bias the evidence base by cherry-picking their own results
default before publication
default. Nothing will improve until such frankly shoddy practices are prevented. This is a challenge for capacity-building, and one that is unadd
defaultressed by high profile programmes such as the UK ‘Quantitative Methods Initiative’ (which are mostly trying to widen the existing invalid practices in this area).
default&#xa0;default5.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn some instances, the lack of efficacy of these interventions may have had more to do with the recruitment and retention of participants than the intervention itself. An intervention to involve parents more, by definition, can only work if the parents wis
defaulth to be involved. In fact, this difference in motivation could be the reason for the widely noted association between parental engagement and child attainment in the first place. Perhaps interventions will never be successful with the unwilling. Potential 
defaultbarriers to enhanced parental involvement include issues with 
defaultparent work schedule and lifestyle, lack of confidence in communicating with school, language, health problems, embarrassment about their own education, negative learner identities, inconsistent
default enthusiasm of teachers for the process, and a 
defaultgeneral lack of interest among some parents. 
