default5.9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor 
defaultusers such as policy-makers and practitioners, 
defaultthe key message 
defaultfrom this review 
defaultis that although increasing parental involvement sounds pl
defaultausible, there is no solid evidence base for intervention yet, in most age groups and for most approaches. Where they are compared with parental involvement interventions, classroom interventions to achieve the same end currently have more evidence of effe
defaultctiveness
default 
defaultin raising attainment. 
default&#xa0;
default5.10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe most promising phase is pre-school and preparation for primary school. 
defaultThe most effective programme in this review, with long term results, and based on some of the best evaluations, mixes parental involvement with an array of other intervention elements. Therefore, it is not possible to conclude that the parental involvement
default element has been effective. Nevertheless, it is worth noting that this programme is based on providing institutional support for parents and bringing them into the care centres and early classrooms. It is not a home-based intervention. In fact, overall, t
defaulthe impression from the review is that interventions are most likely to succeed when they are aimed at young children, and involve parents and staff meeting regularly in an institution, with parental training, on-going support, and co-operative working with
default teachers. 
default&#xa0;
default5.11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is very little evidence of promise from evaluations of parental interventions for children of later primary age, secondary age or across phases of schooling. Practical interventions here can be safely abandoned
default for the present
default, where the
default concern is chiefly with academic outcomes. Some specific kinds of intervention also have so little evidence of promise that they can be abandoned safely (if the concern is chiefly with academic outcomes). These include parents working on
default computers with th
defaulteir children. 
defaultThe remaining approaches can be classified into a number of broad groups. Simple parental participation in school events, like parents-teachers’ evening, or parents-teachers associations, cake sales and other fund-raising events, is untested.
default There is no reason to believe such behaviour will influence attainment for disadvantaged children. 
defaultP
defaultrogrammes that merely encourage parents to work with their children at home (i.e. without direct support or skills training), or seek to improve parent:chi
defaultld relationships
default appear to be ineffective
default. If neither the parent nor the child knows how to improve a skill like reading comprehension then mere aspiration or motivation is not going to help. Effective parental engagement is not just about getting parents 
defaultto be interested in their children’s education or 
defaultto help
default them with their school work. M
defaultany
default parents from all socio-economic backgrounds are already routinely helping with their children’s school work, with low income families just as likely 
defaultto be involved 
defaultas those from higher income homes. And such involvement does not significantly affect children’s performance. So, 
defaultmerely 
defaultincreasing parental involvement is not the answer in itself.
